Introduction to the methods

Manik Garg

03/03/2020

Multi-omics factor analysis (MOFA)

Picture: Argelaguet et al (2020)

MOFA

  • Extension of Factor Analysis
  • Doesn’t require data imputation
  • Finds a shared factor matrix
  • Number of factors can be estimated by providing variance threshold
  • Implemented as Bioconductor package mofa: https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/manuals/MOFA/man/MOFA.pdf

Joint and Individual Variation Explained (JIVE)

Picture: Lock et al (2013)

JIVE

  • Extension of Principal Component Analysis
  • Requires data imputation
  • Finds both joint factor matrix and omics-specific factor matrices
  • Number of factors can be estimated
  • Implemented as R package r.jive: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/r.jive/r.jive.pdf

Multiple co-inertia analysis (MCIA)

  • Extension of Co-intertia Analysis
  • Requires data imputation
  • Finds omics-specific factor matrices but tries to maximize co-intertia between them
  • Number of factors (axes) can be selected interactively from the scree-plot
  • Implemented as Bioconductor package omicade4: https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/manuals/omicade4/man/omicade4.pdf
